The year '''1954 in radio''' involved some significant events. __TOC__
==Events== *1 February: KECA and KECA-FM, both in Los Angeles, change call letters to '''[[KABC (AM)|KABC]]''' and '''[[KLOS|KABC-FM]]''', reflecting their owners, [[ABC News Radio|ABC]]-[[United Paramount Theaters]]. *1 April: [[ABC News Radio|ABC]]-[[United Paramount Theaters]], owners of WENR-Chicago, purchases time-share counterpart '''[[WLS (AM)|WLS]]'''-Chicago from [[Sears, Roebuck and Co.]], and merges both stations under the WLS calls ([[WLS-FM|their FM sister station]] would keep the WENR calls until 1965). *15 July: [[Nippon Broadcasting System]], as known for radio broadcasts station in [[Japan]], first official regular broadcasting service in [[Tokyo]].{{citation needed|date=December 2016}} *17 November: WJW (AM) in [[Cleveland, Ohio]] (today [[WKNR]]) is sold by William M. O'Neill to [[Storer Broadcasting]].
==Debuts== *3 January - [[WAOC|WSTN]] debuts as a 1&nbsp;kW daytimer at St. Augustine, Florida. *9 January - ''Roadshow'' debuts on [[NBC]]. Starring [[Bill Cullen]], the three-hour weekly program is considered a forerunner of the network's ''[[Monitor (NBC Radio)|Monitor]]'', which began a year later.<ref name="coxotd">Cox, Jim (2008). ''This Day in Network Radio: A Daily Calendar of Births, Debuts, Cancellations and Other Events in Broadcasting History''. McFarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-3848-8}}.</ref> *20 January – The [[National Negro Network]] is formed. *6 April - ''[[Crime and Peter Chambers]]'' debuts on [[NBC]].<ref name=dunningota/> *2 September - ''[[Dr. Sixgun]] debuts on [[NBC]].<ref name="dunningota">Dunning, John. (1998). ''On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-507678-3}}.</ref> *3 September - The last original episode of the [[Lone Ranger]] is broadcast.
==Closings== *(undated) - ''[[The Jack Berch Show]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *3 January - ''[[Quiz Kids]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[CBS]]).<ref name=coxotd/> *6 January - ''[[Dr. Christian]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[CBS]]).<ref name=coxotd/> *15 January - ''Double or Nothing'' ends its run on network radio ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]).<ref name=coxotd/> *16 January - ''The Baron and the Bee'' ends its run on network radio ([[NBC]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *5 March - ''[[Family Skeleton]]'' ends its run on network radio (CBS). *12 March - ''[[House of Glass (radio program)|House of Glass]]'' ends its run on network radio (NBC).<ref name=dunningota/> *26 March - ''[[Front Page Farrell]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[NBC]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *27 March - ''[[Twenty Questions]]'' ends its run on network radio.<ref name=coxotd/> *28 March - ''[[Bulldog Drummond (radio program)|Bulldog Drummond]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[Mutual Broadcasting System|Mutual]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *30 March – ''[[Rocky Fortune]]'', a half-hour detective drama starring [[Frank Sinatra]], aired its final episode on [[NBC Red Network|NBC]].<ref name=dunningota/> *22 May - ''[[Armstrong's Theatre of Today|The Armstrong Theater of Today]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[CBS]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *27 May - ''[[Time for Love (radio program)|Time for Love]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[CBS]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *18 June - ''[[The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *24 June - ''[[The Six Shooter]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[NBC]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *9 July - ''[[Can You Top This?]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[NBC]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *1 August - ''[[Broadway Is My Beat]]'' ends its run on network radio ([[CBS]]).<ref name=dunningota/> *7 September -