'''Khaled Fahmy''' ({{lang-ar|خالد فهمي}}) is a historian and the Sultan Qaboos Bin Sa'id Professor of Modern Arabic Studies at the [[University of Cambridge]]. His research interests include the social and cultural history of the modern Middle East, with an emphasis on the history of the army, of medicine and of law in nineteenth-century Egypt.
== Biography == Fahmy received his BA in economics (1985), then an MA in political science (1988) from the American University in Cairo.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} He then received a D Phil in economic and social history at [[St Peter's College, Oxford|St Peter's College]], [[University of Oxford]] in 1993.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} Following his stay at Oxford he became an assistant professor in the Department of Near Eastern Studies at [[Princeton University]] (1994-1999).{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} From 1999 to 2010 he was an associate professor in the Department of Middle Eastern and Islamic Studies at [[New York University]].{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
In 2010, Fahmy returned to Egypt where he was a professor in the Department of History at the American University in Cairo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aucegypt.edu/fac/Profiles/Pages/KhaledFahmy.aspx |title=KHALED FAHMY |publisher=American University of Cairo |accessdate=13 January 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320202739/http://www.aucegypt.edu/fac/Profiles/Pages/khaledfahmy.aspx |archivedate=20 March 2015 |df= }}</ref> In 2014-2015 he was an Arcapita Visiting Professor at the Middle East Institute, [[Columbia University]].{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} In 2015-2016 he was the Shawwaf Visiting Professor in Modern Middle East History at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cmes.fas.harvard.edu/people/shawwaf-visiting-professor|title=Shawwaf Visiting Professor|publisher=Center for Middle Eastern Studies, Harvard University}}</ref> In 2017-2018, he is His Majesty Sultan Qaboos Bin Sa'id Professor of Modern Arabic Studies at [[University of Cambridge]].
== Publications == Fahmy's dissertation on the social history of the army of [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Mehmed Ali Pasha]] was later published by [[Cambridge University Press]] under the title ''All the Pasha's Men: Mehmed Ali: His Army and the Making of Modern Egypt.<ref>'[http://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/history/middle-east-history/all-pashas-men-mehmed-ali-his-army-and-making-modern-egypt]</ref>'' An Arabic translation was published by Dar al-Shorouk. This was followed by a Turkish translation published by Bilgi University Press under the title ''Paşa'nın Adamları:Kavalalı Mehmed Ali Paşa, Ordu ve Modern Mısır''.<ref>[http://www.idefix.com/kitap/pasanin-adamlari-khaled-fahmy/tanim.asp?sid=F4O4NUMU3A7A2IDS22LP]</ref>
Fahmy also wrote a biography of Mehmed Ali Pasha that appeared in the Makers of the Muslim World Series published by Oneworld Publications under the title of ''Mehmed Ali: From Ottoman Governor to Ruler of Egypt''.<ref>[https://www.oneworld-publications.com/books/khaled-fahmy/mehmed-ali#.Vf4XkbSJnww]</ref> He published a collection of articles in Arabic on the history of law and medicine in nineteenth-century that appeared under the title " الجسد والحداثة: الطب والقانون في مصر الحديثة] .<ref>[https://www.abjjad.com/book/2068774912/الجسد-والحداثة-الطب-والقانون-في-مصر-الحديثة/2068807680/reviews]</ref>
In addition to his books, Fahmy has published a number of academic articles on topics including midwifery,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/6736923/_Women_medicine_and_power_in_nineteenth_century_Egypt_in_Lila_Abu_Lughod_ed._Remaking_Women midwifery]</ref> false torture,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=6bbCIigXIuUC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=justice+law+and+pain+fahmy&source=bl&ots=O4rCOETyzf&sig=C57D7G3z0bv5z1VVuGEGbr-Evmo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAWoVChMIqrPFzNKEyAIVBjs-Ch07fgUi#v=onepage&q=justice%20law%20and%20pain%20fahmy&f=false torture]</ref> conscription,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/4921871/The_Nation_and_Its_Deserters_Conscription_in_Mehmed_Alis_Egypt conscription]</ref> cosmopolitanism,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/6736909/The_essence_of_Alexandria_pt._1 Alexandrian]</ref> the census,<ref>[http://britishacademy.universitypressscholarship.com.ezp-prod1.hul.harvard.edu/view/10.5871/bacad/9780197265314.001.0001/upso-9780197265314-chapter-14]</ref> urban planning,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1QofAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ViewAPI#v=onepage&q&f=false]</ref> prisons,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/10734770/Medical_conditions_in_Egyptian_prisons_in_the_nineteenth_century prisons]</ref> the police,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/4921870/The_Police_and_the_People_in_Nineteenth-Century_Egypt]</ref> the smell of the modern city,<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Historians-In-Cairo-Jill-Edwards/dp/9774247019]</ref> forensic medicine,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/6733774/The_Anatomy_of_Justice_Forensic_Medicine_and_Criminal_Law_In_Nineteenth-century_Egypt]</ref> and prostitution<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/6733772/Prostitution_in_nineteenth-century_Egypt prostitution]</ref> – all dealing with nineteenth-century Egypt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://as.nyu.edu/object/KhaledFahmy.html|title=FAHMY, KHALED Representative publications|publisher=New York University|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>
