| [[Aegina]]
| {{sort|AAegina|[[Aegina]]}}<br>([[Greece]])
| {{coord|37.75448|23.53306 | type:landmark_region:GR|name= Temple of Aphaia, Aegina}}
| {{sort|Aphaia|The [[Temple of Aphaea|Temple of Aphaia]]}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|-490}}c.<br>490&nbsp;BC<br>{{r|BF112}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|472.75}}{{cvt|15.5|x|30.5|m|ft|disp=x|}}<br>{{r|FroWiki}}
| {{ntsh|1}}Doric temple which commands a high point on the east side of the island of Aegina, {{cvt|40|km|mi}} from Athens. It has a ''peripteral hexastyle''  plan with 12 columns along each side, showing the development towards temples that were shorter for their width. The interior has a [[hypostyle]] in two stages.{{r|BF1159}} The Doric Order demonstrates great refinement throughout.{{r|Copp48}} Ceramic roof ornaments and [[pediment]]al sculpture showing the battle before [[Troy]] have survived.{{r|Strong59}} No [[metope (architecture)|metope]]s have been found, and it is thought that they were of wood.{{r|Copp44}}
