| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|4900.68}}{{cvt|44.35|x|110.5|m|ft|disp=x|}}<br>{{r|B48}}
| {{ntsh|4 }}A huge Corinthian temple, architect: Cossutius. Built as a gift to Athens by [[Antiochus Epiphanes]] and constructed in 3 stages. It was ''dipteral octastyle'' and was long for its width in the style off the much earlier Archaic period. It had 20 columns on each side and a triple row at the porticos, 104 columns, (diameter: 1.9 metres diameter, height: 17 metres high)(6&nbsp;ft 4 ins; 56&nbsp;ft). Some of the columns were shipped to Rome before the temple was complete and used for the [[Temple of Jupiter Capitolinus]]  where they had a profound effect on Roman architecture. It was completed and dedicated by [[Hadrian]], more than 300 years after it began. Only 15 columns remain.{{r|BF139|B48|BF109140}}
