| {{coord|37.58662|12.83480 | type:landmark_region:IT|name= Temple of Hera, Selinunte}}
| {{sort|Hera8Seli|[[Selinunte|Temple of Hera]],<br/> (Temple "E")}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|-450}}5th&nbsp;century BC<br>{{r|B3941}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|1715.18}}{{cvt|25.32|x|67.74|m|ft|disp=x|}}<br>{{r|B3941}}
| {{ntsh|1 }}The best preserved Doric temple at Selinunte, it is in the eastern group with Temple "F" and Temple "G". It is a ''peripteral hexastyle'' temple with 15 columns at each side, wide aisles and a broad flight of steps to the stylobate.. It has a long narrow naos and inner chamber like other temples at Selinunte but has inner porches at both ends in the Greek manner.{{r|B3941}}
