| [[Selinunte]]
| {{sort|DCastelvetrano|[[Castelvetrano]]}}<br>([[Sicily]]/[[Italy]])
| {{coord|37.58819|12.83491 | type:landmark_region:IT|name= Great Temple of Apollo, Selinunte}}
| {{sort|ApolloCSeli|[[Selinunte|The Great Temple of Apollo]], (Temple "G")}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|-520}}c.<br>520&nbsp;BC - 450&nbsp;BC<br>{{r|BF112}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|5529.04}}{{cvt|50.10|x|110.36|m|ft|disp=x|}}<br>{{r|B3941}}
| {{ntsh|1 }}Doric ''peripteral octastyle'' temple with 18 columns at the sides, in the eastern group at Selinunte, with Temples "E" and "F". It is the largest temple at this site and was never completed. It is now in a state of total ruin. An ambitious building of distinctive plan, having a stylobate rising in two levels and aisles of sufficient width to suggest that either a second row of columns was intended, or that the builders of Sicily, unlike their mainland Greek counterparts, used the trussed roof. The colonnaded inner porch has side, as well as front columns, so that the temple might be termed "pseudo-dipteral". There was a double row of columns within the cella, rising in two stages, of very much more delicate proportions than the exterior colonnade.{{r|B3941}}
