| [[Ephesus]]
| {{sort|BSelçuk|[[Selçuk]]}}<br>([[Turkey]])
| {{coord|37.94968|27.36381}}
| {{sort|ArtemisEphesA|[[Temple of Artemis|The Archaic Temple<br/>of Artemis]]<br/>{{small|(a model of the lost temple)}}}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|-560}}c.<br>560&nbsp;BC,<br/>lost 356&nbsp;BC<br>{{r|BF128}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|5500 }}over 50m x 110m<br/>(appx. 170' x 360')<br>{{r|BF12931}}
| {{ntsh|3 }} One of the ''[[Seven Wonders of the Ancient World]]'', was the fourth temple on the site. It was probably a ''dipteral octastyle'' plan, with columns having up to 48 flutes, and a varied design on the [[Ionic Order|Ionic]] capitals which were each 3 metres wide (10&nbsp;ft). The lower part of each column had an encircling frieze of figures and stood on a deeply moulded [[torus]] and, used here for the first time, a square plinth that was to become an accepted feature of Classical architecture. The temple was burnt out in 356&nbsp;BC and rebuilt.{{r|BF12931}}
