| [[Ephesus]]
| {{sort|BSelçuk|[[Selçuk]]}}<br>([[Turkey]])
| {{coord|37.94968|27.36381}}
| {{sort|ArtemisEphesB|[[Temple of Artemis]]}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|-356}}c.<br>356&nbsp;BC<br>{{r|BF128}}
| style="text-align: center;" |{{ntsh|7662.95}}{{cvt|64.3|x|119.175|m|ft|disp=x|}}<br>{{r|BF12931}}
| {{ntsh|3 }}Ionic temple, architects: [[Demetrius of Alopece|Demetrius]] and [[Paeonius]] of Ephesus; sculptor: [[Scopas]]. Centre of the Pan-Ionian festival. The 5th temple on the site, it was ''dipteral octastyle'' at the front, with the space between the columns increasing towards the central space, where the stone lintel (height: 1.2 metres)(4&nbsp;ft) spanned over 8.5 metres (28&nbsp;ft). At the rear, the temple had 9 columns. The temple's stylobate was raised on a high [[crepidoma]]  (height: 2.75 metres)(9&nbsp;ft). The Ionic capitals were much less wide than those of the Archaic temple, and the columns had the regular 24 flutes. A feature which appears to have been introduced at this temple was the cubic pedestal between the column and its square plinth. The entablature, like others of Asia Minor, had no [[frieze]].{{r|BF12931}}
| [[File:Ac artemisephesus.jpg|150px]]
