{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> | name = Pavao Ritter Vitezović | image = Pavao Ritter Vitezović.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = Paul Vitezović | birth_name = Paulo Ritter<ref name =mtr>{{harvnb|Topić|2010|p=123}}</ref> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1652|01|07|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Senj]], [[Kingdom of Croatia (Habsburg)|Kingdom of Croatia]], [[Habsburg Monarchy]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1713|01|20|1652|01|07|df=y}} | death_place = [[Vienna]], Habsburg Monarchy | occupation = Writer, diplomat }}
'''Pavao Ritter Vitezović''' ({{IPA-sh|pâʋao rîter ʋitěːzoʋitɕ|hr}}; 7 January 1652 – 20 January 1713)<ref>{{harvnb|Fine|2006|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=p3oGybOY1w4C&pg=PA482 p. 482]}}</ref> was a [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]]-[[Kingdom of Croatia (Habsburg)|Croatia]]n writer, diplomat, and publisher known for his expansionism advocacy.
==Early life== Pavao Ritter Vitezović was born as Pavao Ritter in [[Senj]], the son of a [[Military Frontier|frontier soldier]].<ref name=mtr/><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=86SbYzbKvmAC&pg=PA926 Encyclopedia of Historical Writing: A-J] by Daniel R. Woolf</ref> His father was a descendant of an ethnic [[Germans|German]] immigrant from [[Alsace]], and his mother was [[Croats|Croat]].<ref name=mtr/>
He finished six grades of the [[Classical Gymnasium in Zagreb|Jesuit-run gymnasium]] in [[Zagreb]] before moving to [[Rome]], where he stayed at the [[Pontifical Croatian College of St. Jerome|Illyrian College]] and met the renowned Dalmatian historian [[Johannes Lucius|Ivan Lučić]]. He then moved to the castle of [[Bogenšperk Castle|Bogensperk]] ({{lang-de|Wagensberg}}) near the town of [[Litija]] in [[Carniola]], where natural historian [[Johann Weikhard von Valvasor]] influenced him to study his national history and geography. There he also learned [[German language|German]] and the skills of [[printing]] and [[etching]].<ref name="moljac">[http://www.moljac.hr/biografije/vitezovic.htm Profile], moljac.hr; accessed 29 December 2015.{{hr icon}} {{better source|date=August 2014}}</ref>
==Early writings== [[Image:Ritterova kronika (1744).jpg|thumb|''Kronika aliti spomen vsega svijeta vikov'' (1744)]] In 1677 he wrote a treatise on the clan Gusići, published in 1681, the same year he wrote a number of poems for Father Aleksandar Mikulić, a Zagreb [[canon (priest)|canon]]. As he developed a reputation of a learned man, his native town of [[Senj]] elected him as their representative in the [[Hungarian diet]] in [[Sopron]]. On 19 April 1683, due to the efforts of Ritter Vitezović, the Austrian Imperial chancellary proclaimed a charter granting the town of Senj their ancient rights, protecting them from the local military commander captain Herberstein who had terrorised the citizens at the time.<ref>https://www.academia.edu/33565063/Pavao_Ritter_Vitezovic_-_Prigodom_otkrivanja_spomen-ploc_e_u_Bec_u_Scho_nlaterngasse_13_27._VI._2017_</ref>{{Clarify|date=September 2013}}
Because of the [[Ottoman wars in Europe|Ottoman wars]] he was enlisted and stationed in the [[Međimurje]] ''tabor'' (garrison) under [[ban (title)|ban]] [[Nikola Erdödy|Nicholas Erdödy]]. In 1683, when the [[Great Turkish War]] started, he participated in the capture of the forts of [[Lendava]] and [[Szigetvar]]. After the war, ban Erdödy employed him as an officer of his court, where he also met [[Adam Zrinski]], the son of [[Nikola Zrinski]]. He was initially named the ''podžupan'' of [[Lika]] a purely honourable title with no actual significance.<ref>{{harvnb|Topić|2010|p=125}}</ref>
Then [[Croatian Parliament]] named him as their representative in the [[Habsburg Monarchy|Imperial]] commission for the [[delimitation]] with [[Republic of Venice|Venice]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Turkey]], but despite his contribution, the borderlines were drawn against Croatian interests, which greatly frustrated Ritter Vitezović. During his work at the royal and imperial diets in [[Vienna]] and [[Bratislava]], Vitezović met many dignitaries from Croatia, and at one point wished to return home to live in Zagreb.{{cn|date=December 2015}}
==Later years== In 1690, he returned to Croatia,<ref name="moljac"/> where he found out that there was a printing house in the Bishop's Palace in the city of Zagreb, acquired in 1663, but long since abandoned.<ref>{{harvnb|Dobronić|1995|p=172}}</ref> He asked his long-time friend Aleksandar Mikulić, who had by that time been named Bishop,<!-- of what diocese? --> to let him put it to use. He was soon in business, printing calendars and leaflets, and he appealed to the ''Croatian Parliament'' to give that printing house an official capacity. On 11 November 1694, the Parliament did indeed appoint him as the manager of the facility.<ref>{{harvnb|Bratulić|1995|p=181}}</ref> He then proceeded to move it from the Vlaška street to his house on [[Grič, Zagreb|Grič]], and then travelled to Vienna, where he bought a new [[printing press]] and everything else necessary for the printing of books. He named the new printing office the "Museum" (like Valvasor before him), and printed the first books in [[Latin]] and in [[Croatian language|Croatian]].
The printing house was in operation between 1695 and 1706, and his best known work ''Croatia rediviva'' ("Croatia revived") was printed there in 1700. On 14 June 1706, the press was largely destroyed in a great fire, and Vitezović's wife died two years later, rendering him entirely distraught.<ref name="moljac"/>
In 1710 he moved to Vienna, where he continued to publish, and was awarded an honorary title of a baron at the Austrian court. This however did not help his material status before he died in 1713.<ref name="moljac"/>
==Legacy== Ritter Vitezović proposed an idea for orthography solution for the [[Croatian language]] that every sound should have only one letter, and this idea later inspired the linguist [[Ljudevit Gaj]] to reform the Croatian variant of Latin script and create [[Gaj's Latin alphabet]].<ref name="moljac"/>
He created the Croatian [[Exclusivism|exclusivist discourse]] within the early Illyrian movement and introduced the 'historical appropriation' concept to the Balkans which is actually an idea to claim national territory on the basis of the past conquests.<ref name="Trencsényi 2010 220">{{harvnb|Trencsényi|Zászkaliczky|2010|p=220}}</ref><ref name="Macdonald2002">{{cite book|author=David Bruce Macdonald|authorlink=David Bruce Macdonald|title=Balkan Holocausts?: Serbian and Croatian Victim Centered Propaganda and the War in Yugoslavia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kBjrJyen4FEC&pg=PA96|accessdate=4 September 2013|year=2002|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-6467-8|page=96|quote= Ironically, the idea of claiming of national territory based on past occupation or conquest was originally a Croatian one. Pavao Ritter Vitezović [...] would introduce the concept of 'historical appropriation' to the Balkans, and then use it to expand the geographical size of Croatia.}}</ref>
He was the first ideologist of Croatian nation who proclaimed that all [[Slavs]] are [[Croats]].<ref name="Banac1988"/> The foundations of the concept of [[Greater Croatia]] are laid in Vitezović's works.<ref name="AllcockMilivojević1998">{{cite book|author1=John B. Allcock|author2=Marko Milivojević|author3=John Joseph Horton|title=Conflict in the former Yugoslavia: an encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqoUAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=4 September 2013|year=1998|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-87436-935-9|page=105}}</ref> His works were used to legitimize the expansionism of the [[Habsburg Empire]] in [[southeastern Europe]] by asserting its historical rights to claim Illyria.<ref name="Banac1988">{{cite book|last=Banac|first=Ivo|authorlink=Ivo Banac|title=The National Question in Yugoslavia: Origins, History, Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KfqbujXqQBkC&pg=PA73|year=1988|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-9493-1|page=73}}</ref><ref name="Fine 487">{{harvnb|Fine|2006|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=wEF5oN5erE0C&pg=PA487 p. 487]}}</ref> "Illyria" as Slavic territory projected by Vitezović would eventually incorporate not only most of southeastern Europe but also Hungary.<ref>{{harvnb|Trencsényi|Zászkaliczky|2010|p=364}}</ref>
Vitezović defined Croatian territory, as including, besides Illyria and all Slavic-populated territory, the territory between the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]], [[Black Sea|Black]] and [[Baltic Sea|Baltic]] seas.<ref name="Fine 487"/> He also wrote the first [[history of the Serbs]], which remains in manuscript.<ref name="Trencsényi 2010 220"/> He skillfully fabricated numerous genealogies and forged most of the ''Trophaeum nobilissimae domus Estorasianae'' (a genealogical treatise ordered by [[Paul I, Prince Esterházy|Pál Esterházy]]).<ref>{{harvnb|Trencsényi|Zászkaliczky|2010|p=390}}</ref>
