'''Shaikh Ibrahim al-Haidari''' (died after 1860) was an Ottoman historian and anthropologist of the mid-19th century in [[Ottoman Iraq]]. He has been cited as "one of the most perspicacious historians of the period".<ref name="Fattah1997">{{cite book|last=Fattah|first=Hala Mundhir|title=The Politics of Regional Trade in Iraq, Arabia, and the Gulf, 1745-1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g5MewSBHkG4C&pg=PA30|accessdate=13 May 2012|year=1997|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-3113-9|page=30}}</ref> Based in [[Baghdad]], he was the author of a noted regional history of Baghdad, [[Basra]], [[Kuwait]] and [[Najd]] in 1860, in which he "sought to recreate a regional world, tying southern Iraq to Kuwait, Arabistan/Khuzistan and central Arabia.<ref name="BennisMoushabeck1991">{{cite book|last1=Bennis|first1=Phyllis|last2=Moushabeck|first2=Michel|title=Beyond the Storm: A Gulf Crisis Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ki642LknOh0C&pg=PA39|accessdate=13 May 2012|year=1991|publisher=Interlink Books|isbn=978-0-940793-82-8|page=39}}</ref>

